{"/service/ndnp/arhi/batch_arhi_interstellar_ver01/data/sn90050272/00513688714/1920081301/0259.xml":{"full_text":"BUSINESS CRISIS\nOVER U. S. IN SPRING\nMen of Affairs Knew It, But Kept\nSilent.\nThat a serious danger of business\ncrisis did exist in the early spring is\nnow admitted by men who were fa\nmiliar with conditions. They knew it\nat the time but thought that prudence\nrequired silence. Now in these first\ndays of the new fiscal year perhaps\nthe most gratifying report to be made\nis one which tells of the passing of\nthe crisis ami the slow but steady re\nlief from the embarrassments which\nbusiness met with in the winter and\nearly spring.\nThere was no real danger of money\npanic, but business men reported in\nthe spring that they were unable t\nforecast the future for more than a\nfew weeks. They did not know\nwhether they would be able to secure\nneeded accommodations from the\nbanks. They feared lest their loans\nwould be called. The farmers felt\nthe pressure and were obliged to can\ncel orders for tractors and other\nfarm implements. .Many of the sales\nagents were compelled to return to\nthe manufacturers the tractors which\nhad been placed with them for sale.\nWe now know that in the late fall\nof last year the bankers of the United\nStates, at least the leading bankers,\nwere divided into two groups. No\nlonger does a division of tips kind\nexist. One group which was perhap\nthe largest ami most influential began\nin November of last year insist that\nrapid deflation should take place.\nThey asserted that continued inflation\nof tlie currency would not only main\ntain but increase high prices. The\nmeasures they advocated were to a\ngreat extent adopted. Loans were call\ned. There was heavy marketing of\nLiberty bonds, with increasing depre\nciation in their market quotations.\nDeflation was beginning to hurt. The\nsupply of'currency for the business\nof the country was far from suffi\ncient. At the time when business\nwas calling for money the Federal Re\nserve banks were carrying approxi\nmately a billion and a half govern\nment paper. If this money had been\navailable for business embarrassment\nwould not have occurred.\nInsisting on Deflation.\nThroughout the winter and the\nearly spring the pressure for deflation\nwas maintained although it was ap\nparent that there was not enough cur\nrency available for the business life\nof the United States because the gov\nernment through its placing in the\nfederal reserve banks of such enor\nmous amounts of government paper\nhad absorbed it.\nOn the other hand a group of bank\ners in whose membership were a num\nber who had achieved a high reputa\ntion for financial sagacity insisted\nthat the deflation was too rapid and\nthat the attempt to bring it about was\nmade too soon. They went so far as to\nrefer to Great Britain. There the re\nserve of the Bank of England was as\nlow as 15 per cent. Here the reserve\nwas maintained at 10 per cent. Some\nof the banks of the Federal Reserve\nystem were carrying reserves in ex\ncess of 50 per cent, notably Boston.\nReferences were frequent to the re\nmark made in 1907 by the late .1. I\u2019.\nMorgan when he was calling upon the\nbanks for assistance in order that the\npanic in the fall of that year might\nbe ended. Some bankers refused to\ncomply, saying that if they did so\nthey would be compelled to cut into\ntheir reserves. To these bankers Mr.\nMorgan said: \"What are reserves for'\n\u2022xcept for use in emergency\nNotwithstanding the low percent\nage of reserve tarried by the Bank of\nEngland, the I prevailing rates for\nmoney have been satisfactory, Great\nBritain, through its sufficient supply\nof currency and funds, has been able\no overcome some threatened business\nembarrassments.\nTherefore the bankers who feared\nlest deflation was too rapid and too\ndrastic, were in favor of such action\nby the federal reserve system as\nwould make possible an increase of\nthe currency, even though, temporar\nily, this might bring the reserve down.\nGradually the deflation group of\nbankers have changed their opinion.\nThey no longer insist upon drastic\ncutting of loans. They favor reason\nable accommodation for the business\nlife of the country. They believe that\nthere should be sufficient currency in\ncirculation to meet the pressing de\nmand of the business men for accom\nmodation.\nSo it has happened that with this\n\u25a0change of sentiment, deflation has\nended, the chances for an increase in\ncurrency are excellent, and the crisis\nwhich many business men apprehend\ned in the late winter and early spring\nhas passed. Now all look forward\nwith confidence to business activity\nand prosperity, not any longer fearing\nthat drastic deflation will imperil\nbusiness activities and possibly pro\n\u2022luce very great business depression\nfor a time. So that it is the good\nnews of these first days of the new\nfiscal year that the danger of business\ndepression and of crisis has passed.\u2014\nHolland in Wall Street Journal.\nTHE GRAY SPRINGS\nCAMP MEETING\nList night's meetings at Gray\nSprings Camp was the biggest and\nbest of all. Singing, praying, crying,\nshouting rang through the Taber*\nnude till a late hour, ami it was about\nmidnight before the benediction was\npronounced.\nEvangelist Jack Linn preached a\npowerful sermon on the subject \u201cThe\nDetective Who Never Lost a Case,\"\nthe text being, \"Be sure your sin will\nfind you out.\u201d\nWhen the invitation was given, a\ncloud of conviction settled over the\npeople, and many came to the altar.\nThere was a writhing under the bur\n<len of sin which has not been mani\nfested for a long while at this camp, i\nThe choir was unusually good last\nnight and the singing was abundant\nly pleasing to all. Mrs. Linn\u2019s solo\non \u201cThis World Would Be Empty\nWithout Jesus,\u201d her own composition,\nwas well accepted.\nMeeting will close with three serv\nices on Sunday. Those who want to\nbe in an old-time Gospel meeting are\ninvited to come. There is no card\nsinging going on. It is conviction for\nsin and praying through to God,\nCONVICT 1500\nPROFITEERS\nDepartment of Justice Campaign\nBrings Out Lxsl Arrests.\nWashington, Aug. 10.- A total \u201ef\n1.500 convictions have been obtained\nin the campaign of the Department of\nJustice against profiteering, it was\nannounced today. Since the campaign\nwas instituted 1,895 arrests have been\nmade and 1,199 indictments returned.\nSHORT COURSE\nAUG. 17-20\nFayetteville, Aug. 10.\u2014Work of\nspecial interest to women and girls is\nbeing arranged for the women attend\ning the Farmers\u2019 Short Course begin\nning Tuesday, August 17 and contin\nuing to Friday, August 20. A wide\nrange of subjects will be offered so\nthat the farm women can choose work\nthat will best suit their particular\nneed. Practically every subject will\nbe presented to the women by means\nof a demonstration or as a lecture il\nlustrated by lantern slides or films.\nMany of the demonstrations, espe\ncially those in gardening, beekeeping,\nmilking a cow, judging poultry, and\ncanning in tin. will be conducted in\nthe open uir unde\u00a5 the shade trees on\nthe university campus. Canning,\ncookery, bread-making, remodeling\nold clothes, and similar demonstra\ntions will be conducted in the univer\nsity laboratories. The lectures on\nbeautifying the home grounds and on\npoultry work will he given indoors\nwhere lantern slides can be used.\nA large exhibit of washing ma\nchines of all kinds and many labor\nsaving devices will be placed in a tent\non the campus. These machines will\nbe demonstrated each day and lec\ntures will be given on the home\nlaundry equipment and care of cloth\ning.\nTALL BUILDINGS\nCAUSE WINDS\nYou may learn many interesting\nthings about air currents ami the way\nstorms develop by watching the move\nment of pieces of paper, or perhaps\nyour hat, as it is whirled about the\nstreet, A variety of miniature wind\nstorms are developed by the high\nbuildings of our cities or the forms\nof streets, which will repay careful\nstudy. On a hot day even when the\nair is perfectly quiet the atmosphere,\nas it becomes heated tends to rise\nagainst the sides of rocks or build\nings, and if it travels far enough will\ndevelop in a strong wind, which de\nscends on the opposite side and plays\nqueer pranks. A small whirlwind is\noften produced by the action of wind\nagainst a corner formed by several\nbuildings. As the wind travels down\na street again, especially a narrow\nfine, it rapidly increases in velocity.\nA little will spill into the side streets,\nbut the main stream will flow on\ngathering momentum. Watch the\nwind strike against the side of a high\nbuilding and notice how it mushroom*\nout on all sides, splitting into many\ncome to rest, but be sure to hold\ntightly to your hat in the meantime.\nAugust Boys' Life.\nSHE CAN TRI THFULLY S,\\Y\u2014\nHay fever, asthma ami bronchial\ncoughs yield to the soothing, healing\nproperties of Foley\u2019s Honey and Tar\nCompound as quickly and surely as do\nordinary coughs, colds and croup. Mrs.\nGeneva Robinson, 88 N. Swan St., Al\nbany. N. Y., writes: T can truthfully\nsay Foley's Honey nnd Tar is the\nbest cough medicine 1 ever used*\"\nSold by druggists everywhere.\nJULY COTTON REPORT\nArkansas has 2,920,00 i) act. of\ncotton planted this year, promising a\n'yield of 183 pounds of lint to the acre,\nand a total production of 1,120,00')\nbales, based upon the condition fig\nure of 78 per cent of normal crop on j\nInly 25th. This is the estimate made I\nby Charles S. Bouton, Agricultural\nStatistician for the United States Bn\nreau of Crop Estimates, and Jim G.\nFerguson, Commissioner of Agricul\nture.\nFrom the poorest prospect in its\nhistory in May of this year, the crop\nhas increased by leaps and bounds t\nits present condition, and forecasts\nthe second best crop in the history of\nthe state. According to Mr. Bouton,\nthe figures submitted by the volun\ntary reporters were very optimist!-.\nI many of them remarking, \u201cbest pros\npect in years.\u201d There were, however.\nsome negative reports and an occa\nsional discouraged one.\nAbout one-seventh of the reporters,\nmentioned boll weevil, but many of\nthem remarked that though present,\nit did not seem to be doing much dam\nage. Blight was reported by several\nreporters from Crawford and Johnson\ncounties, and by one reporter from i\neach >f the following: Logan, VI. I\nPhillips, St. Francis, and Chicot.\nWorms were reported from tw cour. I\nt ties, Crawford and Scott, in western j\nI Arkansas, and from seven i mnt: I\neastern Arkansas. Rus' was complai:;-\u2018\n|cd of in Franklin, Logan and Yell!\nI counties, in the west, and Columbia\ncounty in the south.\nAs for weather condition- affe\nplant growth, eastern and northeast-I\nlent Arkansas mostly reported \u201ctoo\nj wet.\" Only two auntie- reported j\nI \"too dry.\u201d namely. Arkansas and Lin\ncoln. Complaint of too much rain a.\nso came from Lafayette ami Miller\nCounties in southwest Arkansas, ami\nUnion and Ashley .ounties ::i south\nArkansas.\nThe concensus'of opinion indicating\nthat the crop was still from 12 to It\ndays late for the state as a whole, this\ncondition being most pronounced ii:\nnortheast Arkansas, especially in\nMississippi and Randolph counties.\nLateness was also strongly remarked\nin Howard, Lafayette and Montgom\nery counties in southwest Arkansas,\nthough comments usually declared\nthe condition as improving fast. The\nmajority of correspondents comment\ned on the satisfactory fruiting from\nparts in Franklin county in west Ar\nkansas, and Prairie, Woodruff, and\nAshley Counties in east .Arkansas.\nWilt is present in some of our coun\nties of Central Arkansas, but is ap\nparently doing but little damage.\nThe condition of 78 is I points\nabove the general average of the\nUnited States, which has a condition\nreport of 71 with a prospective pro\nduction of 12.579.01)1) bales. The Ar\nkansas condition of 78 shows a gain\nof 0 points over the condition report I\nof a month ago and is now equal to\nthe 10-year average figure, and 15\npoints in excess of condition figures of\nJuly 25, 1919. A gain of 5 points over\nthe figure of June 25th contrasts with\ni the 10-year average loss of 2 points\nfor that month. The conditibn ami\nacreage figures by counties for hide-\npendence and counties surrounding, is\nherewith appended:\nAcre- COn-\nage dition\nCleburne 13,170 78\nIxanl 28,170 81!.\nSharp 1-1,1)50 83 i\nI Stone 5,990\nIndependence 38,320 8(5\nJackson 59,070 09\nj Lawrence 17.150 77\nLEAGUE OF RED\nCROSS SOCIETIES\nFIGHT TUBERCULOSIS\nRelentless warfrae on tuber, ulosis,\nwhich is reaping almost unhindered;\ntoll among the undernourished *popu-\nlation of Europg, is advocated by the\nMedical Advisory Board of the L\nLeague of Red Ciws Sovieties.\nIncrease in dspensary facilities,-,\nestablishment of open air schools for\nchildren and special education among i\nthe medical profession and the gener-I,\nal public regarding tuberculosis are\nurged. Anti-tuberculosis demonstra\ntions in countries where the disease is i,\nprevalent w ill be created.\nIn formulating the policy of the\nI*eague of Red Cross Societies regard\ning international health improvement\nand disease prevention, intensive\nstudy has been given essential phases\nof the work by the world\u2019s leading\nmedical scientists assemble*! nt Gene\nva. Besides recommending definite\naction in the war on tuberculossi, the\nMedical Board studied plans to com\nbat epidemics, venereal diseases and\nmalaria, and suggested measures for\nthe improvement of child health.\nImmediate organization of a child\nwelfare unit ami special training for\ndoctors and nurses by means of schob\narships by the League of Red Cross\nSocieties are favored as a beginning\nfor improved health among children.\nMakes his truck farm net\n$250 per acre\nReal fanning methods and real\noveralls-~Hennan Moeller has h\nfound the