 on route to Baltimore,\nnecessitating special steps on the part\nof the Baltimore A- Ohio Railroad t\nclear the congestion.\nIn the meantime lit) ships in the\nharbor are awaiting coal to carry to\nforeign ports.\nThat a \u201cspeculative element, fos\ntcred by the niechanism of the Tide\nwater Coal Exchange,\" is responsible I\nfor the chaotic coal situation is the\nopinion expressed by W. C. Andrews\nof the onsolidatisl Coal Cotlipany,\nthe home offices of which are located\nin Baltimore. In support of his state\nment Mr. Andrews said today that of\nthe 2,100. cars at Curtis Bay which the\nBaltimore A\u2019 Ohio Railroad is making\nsp*s ial effort to get unloaded, less\nthan 200 were for nonaffiliated con\nsignees of the Tidewater Coal Ex\nchange.\nWhile an embargo on export coal is\ngenerally conceded to he a remedy for\nthe situation, the possibility of such\nan order being issued is remote, it is\nsaid, due to the fact that the State\nDepartment has let it be known that\nour obligations to foreign govern\nments make it necessary to keep the\nchannel of foreign shipments free\nfrom such an obstruction.\nAdmit Profiteering.\nAdmitting that \u201cthe rankest kind of\nprofiteering\" is going on in the sbft\ncoal trade, local men are divided in\ntheir opinion, however, as to what\nremedy other than the embargo on\nforeign shipments can be effectively\nbrought to bear on the situation.\nI Some, like Mr. Andrews, seem to\nfeel that the abolition of the Tide\nwater Coal Exchange would to a great\nextent overcome the present difficul\nties which legitimate coal operators\nand carriers face.\nC. S. JOHNSON SUC-\nCEEDS L. BUNCH\nU. S Johnson L>gan count) has\nbeen appointed >i nty agent f ir hide\npendence county to succeed Leland\nBur* resigned. Mr. .hihnson .i\nsunie- the dutie- his office Septem\nber I.\nMr. lohn.-ot 'i* s t,, toe >unt>\nwill represent. I IL wa- born an*\nreared in Logan unty. and was edu-\nf ii\nI\nI DRINK FROM THE BOniE\nThe niost\u2019Sanitary Way.